<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="226" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,483,829,888]" box="[151,354,863,888]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,252,863,888]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1850,1872]" captionTargetBox="[176,1416,200,1821]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[162,1426,193,1829]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Neighbor-Joining trees of p-distances based on 1,044 bp of aligned NADH2 sequence data for individual selachian genera or groups of genera. Taxon names are followed by country, host specimen number (in parentheses), and GenBank number. Outgroup taxa used in each analysis were omitted from the individual trees. Scale bar values indicate substitutions per site. Specimens deposited in the Blue Resources Trust Ichthyology Collection are indicted by stars (see text for details). A. Carcharhinus and close relatives (Carcharhinidae). B. Rhizoprionodon (Carcharhinidae). C. Galeocerdidae. D. Hemigaleidae. E. Pseudotriakidae. F. Sphyrnidae. G. Iago (Triakidae)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2637244/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Figs. 4F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[264,290,863,888]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1916,1938]" captionTargetBox="[163,1427,193,1896]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[163,1427,193,1896]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 16. Eusphyra laticeps (Sphyrnidae) (A–C) and Iago cf. omanensis 1 (Triakidae) (D–G). A. Lateral view of mature male (SL-3). B. Dorsal view of head of mature male (SL-3). C. Ventral view of head of mature male (SL-3). D. Lateral view of female (SL-79; BRT-I 0019). E. Ventral view of head of female (SL-79; BRT-I 0019). F. Lateral view of mature male (SL-80; BRT-I 0020). G. Ventral view of head of mature male (SL-80; BRT-I 0020)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2637268/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">16</figureCitation>
A–C)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,935,1501]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">
One of the most intriguing specimens (SL-3) examined in 
<collectingCountry box="[808,918,935,960]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
was caught in the Gulf of Mannar and landed at Palkanththura in the 
<collectingRegion box="[414,690,972,997]" country="Sri Lanka" name="North Western" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">North Western Province</collectingRegion>
. The distinctive narrow blades of its wing-shaped head seemed to unambiguously confirm its identity as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Cuvier)" authorityName="Cuvier" baseAuthorityName="Cuvier" baseAuthorityYear="1816" box="[612,921,1007,1032]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Sphyrnidae" genus="Eusphyra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="blochii">
<emphasis box="[612,810,1007,1032]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Eusphyra blochii</emphasis>
(Cuvier)
</taxonomicName>
. However, it was found to differ from our reference specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cuvier" baseAuthorityYear="1816" box="[420,534,1044,1069]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Sphyrnidae" genus="Eusphyra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="blochii">
<emphasis box="[420,534,1044,1069]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">E. blochii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(AU-83; 
<accessionNumber box="[652,768,1044,1069]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/JQ519152" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">JQ519152</accessionNumber>
) from 
<collectingCountry box="[855,958,1044,1069]" name="Australia" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Australia</collectingCountry>
by 46 bp. This substantial difference in NADH2 sequence suggests that the form from 
<collectingCountry box="[709,823,1079,1104]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
may represent a second species of winghead shark. Although generally considered a synonym of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cuvier" baseAuthorityYear="1816" box="[666,776,1116,1141]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Sphyrnidae" genus="Eusphyra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="blochii">
<emphasis box="[666,776,1116,1141]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">E. blochii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[790,992,1116,1141]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Sphyrnidae" genus="Eusphyra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="laticeps">
<emphasis box="[790,992,1116,1141]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Eusphyra laticeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a candidate name for the Sri Lankan form. This species was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Cantor" box="[562,721,1152,1176]" firstAuthor="Cantor" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" pagination="315 - 320" refId="ref16942" refString="Cantor, T. E. (1837) Description of new species of Zygaena. Calcutta Medical and Physical Society. Quarterly. Article 10, 315 - 320." type="journal article" year="1837">Cantor (1837)</bibRefCitation>
, as 
<taxonomicName authority="Cantor" authorityName="Cantor" authorityYear="1837" box="[763,1038,1151,1176]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Sphyrnidae" genus="Zygaena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="laticeps">
<emphasis box="[763,953,1151,1176]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Zygaena laticeps</emphasis>
Cantor
</taxonomicName>
, from the Bay of Bengal and, based on Cantor’s description, clearly exhibits the extremely expanded head that is diagnostic of 
<emphasis box="[1200,1336,1188,1213]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">E. blochii—</emphasis>
a feature also seen in the specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[501,614,1223,1248]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
. The potential existence of two species with this characteristic head raises an interesting question regarding the identity of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cuvier" baseAuthorityYear="1816" box="[696,806,1260,1285]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Sphyrnidae" genus="Eusphyra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="blochii">
<emphasis box="[696,806,1260,1285]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">E. blochii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for which the 
<typeStatus box="[973,1021,1261,1285]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">type</typeStatus>
locality is unknown (
<bibRefCitation author="Gilbert" box="[1268,1424,1260,1285]" firstAuthor="Gilbert" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" pagination="1 - 88" refId="ref18289" refString="Gilbert, C. R. (1967) A revision of the hammerhead sharks (family Sphyrnidae). Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 119, 1 - 88. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.119 - 3539.1" type="journal article" year="1967">Gilbert, 1967</bibRefCitation>
), but which is currently considered to be distributed throughout the Indo-West Pacific (
<bibRefCitation author="Compagno" box="[1132,1332,1296,1320]" firstAuthor="Compagno" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" refId="ref17157" refString="Compagno, L. J. V. (1984) FAO Species Catalogue. Fol. 4. Sharks of the World. An Annotated and Illustrated Catalogue of Shark Species Known to Date. Part 1. Hexanchiformes to Lanniformes. FAO Fisheries Synopsis. No. 125, FAO, Rome, Italy, 249 pp." type="book" year="1984">Compagno, 1984</bibRefCitation>
). Clearly examination of additional specimens and comparison with specimens from other localities in the Indo-West Pacific is in order.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,935,1501]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">
It seems likely that this is the taxon in 
<collectingCountry box="[661,774,1404,1429]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
referred to as 
<taxonomicName authority="Cuvier" authorityName="Cuvier" box="[949,1217,1404,1429]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Sphyrnidae" genus="Sphyrna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="blochii">
<emphasis box="[949,1131,1404,1429]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Sphyrna blochii</emphasis>
Cuvier
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Goonewardene" firstAuthor="Goonewardene" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" pagination="1 - 3" refId="ref18337" refString="Goonewardene, T. P. (1971) The hammerhead sharks in Ceylon Seas (family Sphyrnidae). Bulletin of the Fisheries Research Station, Ceylon, 22, 1 - 3." type="journal article" year="1971">Goonewardene (1971)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="De Silva" box="[280,459,1439,1464]" firstAuthor="De Silva" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" pagination="225 - 232" refId="ref17467" refString="De Silva, R. I. (1977) A guide to some sharks of Sri Lanka. Loris, 14, 225 - 232." type="journal article" year="1977">De Silva (1977)</bibRefCitation>
and as 
<taxonomicName box="[544,653,1439,1464]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Sphyrnidae" genus="Sphyrna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="blochii">
<emphasis box="[544,653,1439,1464]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">E. blochii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="De Silva" box="[695,865,1439,1464]" firstAuthor="De Silva" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" pagination="56 - 66" refId="ref17520" refString="De Silva, R. I. (1984 - 1985) The sharks of Sri Lanka. A key to the different species and a preliminary checklist. Ceylon Journal of Science (Biological Sciences), 17 - 18, 56 - 66." type="book chapter" year="1984">
De Silva (
<date box="[807,865,1439,1464]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" value="1984" valueMax="1985">1984</date>
</bibRefCitation>
–1985, 2006, 2015), 
<bibRefCitation author="De Bruin" box="[1098,1348,1439,1464]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="De Bruin" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" refId="ref17417" refString="De Bruin, G. H. P., Russell, B. C. &amp; Bogusch, A. (1995) FAO Species Identification Field Guide for Fisheries Purposes. The Marine Fishery Resources of Sri Lanka. FAO, Rome, Italy, 400 pp." type="book" year="1995">
De Bruin 
<emphasis box="[1208,1264,1439,1464]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">et al.</emphasis>
(1995)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Moron" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Moron" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" pagination="142 - 157" refId="ref19181" refString="Moron, J., Bertrand, B. &amp; Last, P. (1998) A check-list of sharks and rays of western Sri Lanka. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of India, 40, 142 - 157." type="journal article" year="1998">
Morón 
<emphasis box="[151,207,1476,1501]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">et al.</emphasis>
(1998)
</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Joseph" box="[350,492,1476,1501]" firstAuthor="Joseph" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" pagination="339 - 366" refId="ref18550" refString="Joseph, L. (1999) Management of shark fisheries in Sri Lanka. In: Shotton, R. (Ed.), Case Studies of the Management of Elasmobranch Fisheries. FAO Fisheries Technical Paper. No. 3780, Rome, Italy, pp. 339 - 366." type="book chapter" year="1999">Joseph 1999</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
